{{Geography Page}}
=Piedmont= ''from the [https://nabci-us.org/resources/bird-conservation-regions-map/#bcr29 US NABCI] website:''
The Piedmont is transitional between the mountainous Appalachians and the flat coastal plain and is dominated by pine and mixed southern hardwoods. Priority landbirds include [[Red-cockaded Woodpecker]], [[Bachman's Sparrow]], and [[Brown-headed Nuthatch]]. Interior wetlands, reservoirs, and riverine systems provide migration and wintering habitat for waterfowl and some shorebirds. The fragmented patchwork of pasture, woodlots, and suburban sprawl that now dominates most of this region creates significant bird conservation challenges.
[[Category:Geography]][[Category:Bird Conservation Region]] {{#set: Has Geography=Atlantic Coast Joint Venture |Has Organization=United States North American Bird Conservation Initiative |Has Species=Red-cockaded Woodpecker |Has Species=Bachman's Sparrow |Has Species=Brown-headed Nuthatch |Has Geography=Atlantic Coast Joint Venture Region |Has Geography=Atlantic Flyway |Has Organization=Atlantic Coast Joint Venture |Has Organization=Partners in Flight Eastern Working Group |Has Plan=North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan |Has Plan=North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan 2015 }}

{{Geography Page}} {{NC Ecoregions}} =Description= The Coastal Plain ecoregion includes mid-Atlantic areas east of the fall line and the tidal coast (ocean, sounds, barrier islands, and mainland brackish and salt marshes). It may be divided roughly into two sections: the tidewater area (lower Coastal Plain), which is largely flat and swampy, and the interior portion (upper Coastal Plain), which is made up of gently sloping elevations and is better drained than other regions. The upper Coastal Plain encompasses the Sandhills ecoregion. The average elevation is from about 200 feet at the fall line (or western boundary separation from the Piedmont), sloping to an elevation of generally 50 feet or less over most of the mainland landscape, with barrier islands being close to sea level.
Eastern North Carolina is home to longleaf pine ecosystems, wetlands, maritime forests and other critical habitats for terrestrial and aquatic species.
[[Category:Geography]][[Category:Ecoregion]] {{#set: Has Geography=North Carolina |Has Organization=North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission |Has Habitat=Category:Aquatic Communities |Has Habitat=Caves and Mines |Has Habitat=Dry Longleaf Pine Communities |Has Habitat=Estuarine Aquatic Communities |Has Habitat=Estuarine Wetland Communities |Has Habitat=Floodplains-Blackwater Systems |Has Habitat=Floodplains-Brownwater Systems |Has Habitat=Floodplains-Inland Systems |Has Habitat=Freshwater Tidal Wetlands |Has Habitat=Groundwater, Springs/Caves |Has Habitat=Headwater Streams/Small Creeks |Has Habitat=Large River Systems |Has Habitat=Low Elevation Flatrocks, Cliffs, and Rock Outcrops |Has Habitat=Maritime Forests |Has Habitat=Maritime Grasslands |Has Habitat=Medium River Systems |Has Habitat=Mesic Forests |Has Habitat=Natural Lakes |Has Habitat=Nonalluvial Mineral Wetlands |Has Habitat=Oak and Mixed Hardwood/Pine Forests and Managed Timber |Has Habitat=Pocosins |Has Habitat=Reservoirs and Impoundments |Has Habitat=Sand, Shell, and Wrack Active Shoreline |Has Habitat=Small River Systems/Large Creeks |Has Habitat=Sparsely Settled Mixed Habitats |Has Habitat=Stream Swamps |Has Habitat=Successional Communities |Has Habitat=Upland Pools and Depressions |Has Habitat=Upland Seepages and Spray Cliffs |Has Habitat=Warmwater Streams |Has Habitat=Wet Pine Savannas |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 195 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 231 }}

{{Geography Page}} {{NC Ecoregions}} =Description= The Mountain ecoregion includes all portions of the Southern Appalachian Mountains that occur west of the Blue Ridge Escarpment. There are several foothill ranges (the Brushy, Sauratown, and South mountains) located within the Piedmont province that are part of the Mountain ecoregion. North Carolina has the highest elevations of any state east of the Mississippi River, with Mount Mitchell being the highest peak at 6,684 feet (all elevations are above mean sea level).
From high peak spruce-fir forests to low floodplain valleys, the mountainous western region of North Carolina provides specialized habitat for a broad array of biodiversity. Natural community descriptions and priority conservation action recommendations can be found in Chapter 4 of the 2015 [[North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan|N.C. Wildlife Action Plan]] (NCWAP).
[[Category:Geography]][[Category:Ecoregion]] {{#set: Has Geography=North Carolina |Has Habitat=Bogs and Fens |Has Organization=North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission |Has Habitat=Category:Aquatic Communities |Has Habitat=Caves and Mines |Has Habitat=Coldwater Streams |Has Habitat=Coolwater Streams |Has Habitat=Cove Forests |Has Habitat=Dry Coniferous Woodlands |Has Habitat=Grass and Heath Balds |Has Habitat=Groundwater, Springs/Caves |Has Habitat=Headwater Streams/Small Creeks |Has Habitat=High Elevation Cliffs and Rock Outcrops |Has Habitat=Low Elevation Flatrocks, Cliffs, and Rock Outcrops |Has Habitat=Mafic Glades and Barrrens |Has Habitat=Maritime Forests |Has Habitat=Medium River Systems |Has Habitat=Montane Oak Forests |Has Habitat=Northern Hardwood Forests |Has Habitat=Oak and Mixed Hardwood/Pine Forests and Managed Timber |Has Habitat=Reservoirs and Impoundments |Has Habitat=Small River Systems/Large Creeks |Has Habitat=Sparsely Settled Mixed Habitats |Has Habitat=Spruce-Fir Forest |Has Habitat=Successional Communities |Has Habitat=Upland Pools and Depressions |Has Habitat=Upland Seepages and Spray Cliffs |Has Habitat=Warmwater Streams |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 116 }}

{{Geography Page}} {{NC Ecoregions}} =Description= The Piedmont ecoregion includes the areas east of the foot of the Blue Ridge Escarpment and west of the fall line, excluding the foothill ranges that are part of the Mountain ecoregion. The fall line is a major break in geologic structure between the Piedmont and the Coastal Plain which results in differences in ecosystem patterns and a variety of landscape relief and roughness. Elevations range from about 1,500 feet in the foothills to about 200 feet at the fall line.
North Carolina’s classic Piedmont habitats include old fields, rock outcrops, streams and woodlands, where species diversity for some animal groups, such as amphibians, reptiles and birds, is relatively high.
[[Category:Geography]][[Category:Ecoregion]] {{#set: Has Geography=North Carolina |Has Habitat=Bogs and Fens |Has Organization=North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission |Has Habitat=Category:Aquatic Communities |Has Habitat=Caves and Mines |Has Habitat=Coldwater Streams |Has Habitat=Dry Coniferous Woodlands |Has Habitat=Dry Longleaf Pine Communities |Has Habitat=Groundwater, Springs/Caves |Has Habitat=Headwater Streams/Small Creeks |Has Habitat=Low Elevation Flatrocks, Cliffs, and Rock Outcrops |Has Habitat=Mafic Glades and Barrrens |Has Habitat=Maritime Forests |Has Habitat=Medium River Systems |Has Habitat=Mesic Forests |Has Habitat=Oak and Mixed Hardwood/Pine Forests and Managed Timber |Has Habitat=Reservoirs and Impoundments |Has Habitat=Small River Systems/Large Creeks |Has Habitat=Sparsely Settled Mixed Habitats |Has Habitat=Successional Communities |Has Habitat=Upland Pools and Depressions |Has Habitat=Upland Seepages and Spray Cliffs |Has Habitat=Warmwater Streams |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 117 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 118 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 234 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 472 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 288 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 567 |Has Priority=NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 590 }}

{{Geography Page}}
=Southeastern Coastal Plain= ''from the [https://nabci-us.org/resources/bird-conservation-regions-map/#bcr27 US NABCI] website:''
This region includes extensive riverine swamps and marsh complexes along the Atlantic Coast. Interior forest vegetation is dominated by longleaf, slash, and loblolly pine forests. Priority landbirds include the [[Red-cockaded Woodpecker]], [[Painted Bunting]], [[Bachman's Sparrow]], [[Swainson's Warbler]], and [[Swallow-Tailed Kite]]. Coastal intertidal habitats provide critical wintering areas for American Oystercatcher, important wintering and spring migration areas for Short-billed Dowitcher and Dunlin, and important fall staging areas for Red Knot. Sizable numbers of [[Brown Pelican]]s and various terns breed on offshore islands. Coastal areas provide important nesting and foraging habitats for large numbers of herons, egrets, ibis, terns, and other species. Coastal areas winter large numbers of [[Canvasback]], [[Mallard]], [[American Wigeon]], [[Redhead]], and the majority of the continent’s population of Tundra Swans. Managed impoundments in coastal areas are important to migrating and wintering dabbling ducks, including [[American Black Duck]].
[[Category:Geography]][[Category:Bird Conservation Region]] {{#set: Has Geography=Atlantic Coast Joint Venture |Has Organization=United States North American Bird Conservation Initiative |Has Species=Red-cockaded Woodpecker |Has Species=Painted Bunting |Has Species=Bachman's Sparrow |Has Species=Swainson's Warbler |Has Species=Swallow-Tailed Kite |Has Species=Brown Pelican |Has Species=Canvasback |Has Species=Mallard |Has Species=American Wigeon |Has Species=Redhead |Has Species=American Black Duck |Has Geography=Atlantic Coast Joint Venture Region |Has Geography=Atlantic Flyway |Has Organization=Atlantic Coast Joint Venture |Has Organization=Partners in Flight Eastern Working Group |Has Organization=United States Shorebird Conservation Partnership |Has Plan=North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan |Has Plan=North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan 2015 |Has Plan=South Atlantic Migratory Bird Initiative Implementation Plan 2008 }}

{{Geography Page}}
=Appalachian Mountains= ''from the [https://nabci-us.org/resources/bird-conservation-regions-map/#bcr28 US NABCI] website:''
Included in this area are the Blue Ridge, the Ridge and Valley Region, the Cumberland Plateau, the Ohio Hills, and the Allegheny Plateau. The rugged terrain is generally dominated by oak-hickory and other deciduous forest types at lower elevations and by various combinations of pine, hemlock, spruce, and fir in higher areas. While flatter portions are in agricultural use, the majority of most segments of this region are forested. Priority forest birds include [[Cerulean Warbler]] at low elevations and [[Black-throated Blue Warbler]] at high elevations. [[Golden-winged Warbler]]s are in early successional areas, and [[Henslow's Sparrow]]s are in grasslands. While not as important for waterfowl as coastal regions, the Appalachian region contains the headwaters of several major eastern river systems that are used by various waterfowl species during migration. In addition, large wetland complexes, such as Canaan Valley in West Virginia, and isolated beaver-created wetlands provide habitat for Wood Duck breeding.
[[Category:Geography]][[Category:Bird Conservation Region]] {{#set: Has Geography=Appalachian Mountain Joint Venture Region |Has Organization=United States North American Bird Conservation Initiative |Has Species=Cerulean Warbler |Has Species=Black-throated Blue Warbler |Has Species=Golden-winged Warbler |Has Species=Henslow's Sparrow |Has Geography=Atlantic Flyway |Has Organization=Appalachian Mountain Joint Venture |Has Organization=Partners in Flight Eastern Working Group |Has Plan=North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan |Has Plan=North Carolina Wildlife Action Plan 2015 }}

